On January 18, 2010, President Obama, First Lady Michelle Obama, and several Cabinet Secretaries and senior Administration officials participated in community service projects around Washington, DC to celebrate the Martin Luther King, Jr. National Day of Service. Led by the Corporation for National and Community Service and the King Center, this day is an opportunity for Americans to come together and serve their communities. The projects included delivering meals, refurbishing schools, reading to children, promoting nonviolence, and more. President Obama encouraged Americans to make service a part of their lives every day. Various officials participated in different projects, such as serving food to the homeless, preparing meals for the needy, participating in clean-up and beautification projects, visiting underprivileged care recipients, and more. The goal was to honor Dr. King's legacy by helping others and strengthening communities.